Detailed Description

Evaluates multiple expressions in XPath style and calls the associated NodeEvaluator for each node it finds.

Note: Only use the multiplier '*' on the first node. For example: 

   /result_yp/adverts/@count
   /result_yp/adverts/@hits
   /result_yp/adverts/advert*
   /result_yp/adverts/advert/company_info/company_name
   /result_yp/adverts/advert/company_info/email
Notice how the '*' operator is not included for advert before company_info. An attribute is declared as: /result_yp/adverts/ This will try to find attribute count in node adverts . Attributes do not have a multiplier option. The evaluation can also handle namespace, such as "namespace:nodename".

Example usage: 

 class Eval: public NodeEvaluator {
 public:
    void operator() ( const DOMNode* node ) { ... }
 };

 NodeDescription desc[] {
   { "/root/child*", new Eval() },
   { "/root/child/value2", new Eval() },
 };

 MultiExpression exp( MultiExpression::
                      Description( desc, desc +
                                   sizeof( desc ) / sizeof( desc[ 0 ] ) ) ); 

 
 DOMNode* root = ... parse xml document ... ;
 exp.evaluate( root );

Constructor & Destructor Documentation

XMLTool::XPath::MultiExpression::MultiExpression (  const Description &  nodes,
const MC2String &  nspace = MC2String(),
bool  removeNamespace = false
)  [explicit]
 

Generates an evaluation tree to be used for evaluating nodes The m_evaluator in NodeDescription will be owned and deleted by this instance.

The param nspace sets the namespace prefix to be used when comparing nodes. This param will be used as "namespace:node" comparision with the expressions "node" name. For example: expression "/first/second" with namespace "ab" will be evaluated as "/ab:first/ab:second" .

Parameters:
nodes Expressed as vector of NodeDescriptions.
nspace The namespace name.
removeNamespace If to remove namespaces from DOMElements when comparing paths with nodes in a DOMDocument. This might lead to problems if namespaces are used to sperarate different nodes with the same name.
